text:
A couple of points:
1. Steve doesn't seem to be wearing an elytra when he jumps off
2. The only names shown in the subtitles are Steve and VP Marlene
3. The creeper walking is shown as 'crunching' in the subtitles, possible referring to the original idea of creepers being like plants
4. The subtitles say 'nitwit groaning' when the villager gets hit
5. In the opening scene, when Steve does a water bucket clutch, the other characters are wearing elytra, probably suggesting they don't know how to use them properly yet
6. When the pandas fall back to the ground, you can see the separate parts of the elytra stuck in the ground
7. There are apples on the trees at 0:25
8. At 0:33 there's a full theme park with a rollercoaster in the right of the background
9. When Garrett Garrison says "Vaya con Dios," it seems the group is heading back into the real world
10. At 1:09, in the upper right, there is a hanging sign that says 'Steve's Lava Chicken!'
11. At 1:10, Steve is holding a sword and shield, and the kid is holding an item that looks a bit like a megaphone (edit: apparently it's a potato cannon, thanks @TheOneWhoTalksALot)
11. At 1:35, Steve seems to be holding onto Garrett Garrison since Steve doesn't have an elytra
12. At 1:38, when the creeper lights up, there seems to be the creeper's skeleton visible inside
13. At 2:00, there are pillagers around the boxing ring
14. At 0:21, the dog teleports to Steve as he builds the villager heads (ty to @mazekart4972 and @microvive30)
15. At 0:16 there are dolphins jumping out of the water in the bottom-right (ty @HunterTheHero)

text: I'm kind of disappointed. The original story of "In the Lost Lands" is a pretty simple fantasy story of Grey Alys heading to the lost lands in search of a werewolf for a knight that paid her to get one. And she hires Boyce to be her guide. The Lost Lands are post-catastrophic, there was a civilization there but no longer, but this weird pseudo western story has neither the charm nor the compelling character of the original. The story is about philosophy and the nature of humans and their desires, not brainless action.

text: For those who don't know: Bong Joon Ho is one of the best directors in the world, straight up. He rivals Park Chan Wook as the best director working in South Korea. His best movie is Memories of Murder, but he's also made several others including The Host, Snowpiercer, Okja, and Parasite. His movies are known for being disturbing and representing the dark side of humanity, but this one seems like he's going for a dark comedy/satirical approach which could work really well. I would strongly recommend watching his earlier movies so you can understand his vibe.

text:
Positives : 
Gal Gadot look stunning.
Zegler can sing.

Negatives.
You tried to hide it, but you can still tell that this is a girl boss movie. 
Thematically this would not be an issue but, unfortunately the actress playing Snow White made it impossible to separate the character from the actress. 

She might have very well played the best Snow White on screen but many will see a "Mean, Disrespectful, and very Unlikeable" person as Snow White.
That will ultimately hurt sales for this movie.

The CG in the movie looks really good in certain scenes, but more often then not, pulls you out of immersion with really bad uncanny valley images. The Dwarves in particular just didn't quite translate well during the animation process, they really should have used live actors.

All in all, hope that those who can enjoy this movie will do so, for me, Snow White's departure from the true innocent as portrayed in the original movie and the radical change to the story (and in essence, the soul of this story) is just too much of a stretch and neither I nor my family will be supporting it.

text:
Everyone here is predicting that the killer will be motivated by a loneliness induced  hatred of couples, which is fairly reasonable. But what if the twist is  the complete opposite: that there‚Äôs actually two killers, they‚Äôre a couple, and their idea of a double date is killing other couples.
































Edit: Thanks for all the likes! I have now seen the movie. I loved it! I think there are some pacing issues in the drive-in theater scene, and the climax has some obnoxious exposition and confusing circumstances surrounding a bullet wound, but overall, the film was consistently thrilling, funny, and sweet throughout. 

The opening scene is incredibly strong and establishes the tone, visual style, and humor of the film very well. I loved the cinematography throughout: I enjoyed its color palette, and something about the film‚Äôs compositions really appeals to me. 
 
I found the characters likable and very well performed. I loved how they fought the killer together, it was a great way to marry the slasher and romance genres, transforming the act of fighting a serial killer into a method by which the couple could bond. 

I have mixed thoughts on the killer‚Äôs costume. I love the heart eyes, and in the right lighting (as seen in the poster, which notably enshrouds the entirety of their lower body in darkness), the costume looks great. But in some ways, it‚Äôs generic. I do like the silhouette and movement of their coat, but its pure black color scheme is kind of uncreative and clashes with the mask, which I think is meant to be evocative of a cherub, and doesn‚Äôt really have anything to do with the rest of the costume. 

Perhaps they could have added something evocative of wings to the coat to bridge the head to the rest of the body. I also have mixed thoughts on the mask: I can‚Äôt decide whether I like or dislike its veiny texture. On another note, the killer‚Äôs arsenal is great and fits their motif very well.

Overall, I had great time, and of course, it was great to see my prediction was somewhat correct! I give it a 7-8/10, or a 75-80/100. My thoughts on some of the film‚Äôs aspects are not entirely set in stone, but I‚Äôm fairly positive about these scores. I recommend it if you can handle gore and are in the mood for a likable comedy-horror film.

text: It seems like they made this trailer in response to the complaints of the previous one. The only line Kraven has is in russian this time, which conceals that he has no accent whatsoever. They also didn't bring up the whole "animal powers" thing that the last trailer showed, which was about as bizarre as when they gave Jonah Hex superpowers in his movie. This trailer also makes Kraven seem more threatening and villainous, like the comic one, rather than the hero of the story against his villainous father. Not sure what to believe here, but the first trailer probably has more reality in it.

People here in the comment section comparing it to Midsommar tend to forget that Midsommar dealt with trauma, grief, cheating, toxic relationship, cults, culture, paganism and other heavy/intelligent themes, while this deals with fame and lack of punishment for the rich. text:
I will never forget reading this at university, on my own in the basement of the halls of residence, doing my laundry. 

If you put your clothes in the washing machine and left some sicko would stop the machine, take your clothes out and put their own in, so I started sitting with the machine and waiting for it to finish.

Reading The Monkey and got to a part where the monkey was just about to smash his cymbals together and the fire alarm goes off. I think there's still an imprint on the ceiling of my head from the jump I did.

Someone is using the monkey as a weapon, or the monkey is using them as an assistant. At 1:31, the person who brings the monkey into that shop can be seen stepping back and out of the way while staring at the monkey. This implies they know what‚Äôs it‚Äôs doing, which further implies that they brought it there knowing it would kill. The only reasons one would do such a thing are on behalf of the monkey, or in order to use its power. 

Alternatively, the hurried and almost panicked way they brought it into the store suggests that they were trying to get rid of it by selling it to the shop owner, or were made aware of its intent to kill someone and were desperately searching for someone to sacrifice to the monkey, in lieu of themselves.

text: A few months ago, before I made my channel, I found a captain underpants iceberg video and one thing that caught my attention was a part about a dog man movie. A few months after I watched that video, this came out. As a recent dog man reader, I have had an obsession with the series from book 1. I genuinely love how the characters sound, look, and how vibrant the movie is. This could really capture an audience. I also love how they made the news reporter have an australian accent because in dog man and cat kid, when Yolay said "Hooray for Italy!" in italian, the news reporter says "But I'm Australian." I have so much genuine excitement for this movie. I love how the style of the eyes reference the eye style from the captain underpants movie. The cartoony style/vibe/feel/look make the trailer look 100 times better. Petey's lab looks like how it does in the book. Petey seems like such a villain in the movie especially when the news reporter lady says "How evil can one cat be!?" and Petey says "Pretty Evil!" Can't wait, and I be at the theater in a heartbeat on January 31st 2025.

text:
The budget for this movie is $250 million and there is no way in he|| this movie should have cost that much. The entire movie looks cheap like it was shot on soundstage and green screen with little to no location shooting or in camera practical effects.

Dwayne‚Äôs base salary alone is $50 million not including his backend residuals, the marketing spend is likely at least nine figures so including distribution and theatrical commissions, this movie would need to break at least $650 million worldwide to turn a profit which it won‚Äôt because it will flop big time. And attaching the Amazon name so prominently on the marketing is a box office killer, it keeps people from the theater since they will assume they can watch on Prime within 30 days of theatrical release.

Maybe Amazon doesn‚Äôt care because they have money to burn but the financials for this movie make absolutely no sense. No wonder Dwayne‚Äôs career is declining, his recent movies have been flops and no studio greenlights his productions anymore.

It would be great to see a Johnathan Majors comeback from this.  Also just a little side note, but its crazy how Majors got so insanely jacked for this, but compared to the actual Olympia competitors he is so tiny in this movie. text: As someone that went on a Mormon mission as a sister missionary, first rule, don't enter the home of someone of the opposite sex if there is no one of your sex in the home.................. lol, they broke the first rule, lol, anyways, I will admit there were times on the mission, and I went stateside too, where it was a little bit scary to talk to certain people, honestly was afraid of something like this happening, especially when I found out the BTK serial killer was found one neighborhood over from where I was serving at the exact time he was found, lol,  geez, lol.. Anyways, no matter what you believe about the church, and I'm not practicing anymore for various reasons, those Mormon missionaries are literal kids, thrown into situations that maybe they shouldn't be in, there have been times missionaries have been kidnapped for ransom in areas of the world they probably shouldn't have been proselytizing in, and they are even younger now than when I was out, younger than when my aunt went on her to Seoul in the early 80s (she should've never have gone there, there was a political coup that happened when she was there, then deadly student protests right after she left), if you come across Mormon missionaries out and about in your area of the world, be nice to them, you don't have to let them teach you or even engage with them, they are technically spreading propaganda to be honest, but be kind to them and look out for them.

text: From the Wiki about Tolkien's Helm Hammerhand story: The scene about the arranged marriage appears to be accurate to the book. The Wiki then says this incident started a war between the tribes, initiated by the "evil" tribe seeking revenge against Helm's tribe for the death of their leader. One thing that's not in the story is any mention of Helm's daughter outside of her being part of the attempted arranged marriage. Helm, his two sons and his nephew fight in the war, but not her. She isn't even given a name in the book, although the other characters are. So, everything in this trailer involving Helm's daughter, after the marriage incident, is apparently an invention of the movie's writers.

text:
Positive:
- Miranda Otto's narration sounds perfect
- Beautiful scenery such as Helm's Deep, Edoras, the high mountains, and forests. Each location feels distinct and cohesive in its aesthetic
- The horses are very well-drawn
- The men of the Rohirrim are dressed excellently, and outfits are varied according to whether they are at leisure, riding to war, etc., but still with a cohesion that conveys a well-fleshed out culture
- Helm's daughter's dresses in the beginning shots are beautiful, reminiscent of Miranda Otto as Eowyn without being identical
- Inclusion of a range of more fantastical Middle Earth features (e.g. Orcs, Great Eagles, Mumakil, a creature similar to the Watcher of the Deep)
- Great line delivery by a number of characters (e.g. Brian Cox: "My pride, my joy")
- Multiple perspectives (e.g. Helm's daughter on her journey vs  the Rohirrim defending Rohan) and subplots (e.g. the person collecting rings) - hopefully these will be well-balanced and interwoven

Negative:
- Multiple LOTR clips for the first 15-20 seconds feels a little heavy handed (though this is a minor point, as the transition with "through the eyes of legendary director Kenji Kamiyama" was good)
- Dunlending outfits look a tad generic (with the exception of Wulf and his father)
- Brian Cox's delivery of his speech to his men might be accused of drawing too heavily from Bernard Hill
- Miranda Otto's voice randomly cuts out at 0:28
- Lip syncing to line delivery is not always good
- Not a lot of Helm Hammerhand
- Helm's daughter's riding outfit seems very out of place with the rest of the outfits in the film

text:
Showing us clips of LOTR at the beginning, like some nice 'member berries, shows you'll don't believe in your product to stand on its own two legs.
The animation looks basic and cheap - there are current animes that look more beautiful than this.
Studio Ghibli pioneered anime being "ethereal" and you see his influence in a lot of non-StudioGhibli productions as well.

text:
The thought of being 100 meters underwater feels less psychologically terrifying, though I‚Äôve already decided not to watch the movie because I have a deep fear of situations like that. Being trapped in a setting like the one in "Gravity" feels just as horrifying. Yet, it's odd how knowing it‚Äôs ‚Äúonly‚Äù 100 meters deep makes it slightly less dreadful, even though the risk to life is still there. Being so far removed from human lives and anything familiar. I think it's that isolation that‚Äôs so unsettling for me. 

I understand this story is based on true events, and I saw comments from the diver‚Äôs in-laws below. I mean no disrespect. Just sharing some thoughts I found psychologically interesting. At first, I thought it was set in the deep ocean, like Victor Vescovo‚Äôs expedition six miles below the surface.

text: The sound effects of the facehugger and chestburster are brutal, love it. I'm so happy to see the franchise in the hands of someone who truly gets why Alien and Aliens are such masterpieces in their own right. You can literally watch Aliens first and Alien second and it would take away little from the overall experience. To (seemingly) be able to capture  the essence of both movies and still manage to bring your own style into it by for instance leaning into the body horror. Then even go big on the practical and not get caught into doing it all with CGI. Fede is already making history within the franchise with what we've seen so far, that is impressive. I thought I'd never see the day that I would be counting the days to go see an Alien movie once again. I thought that ship had sailed and the abstract vision Ridley Scott gave us deserves praise too. Despite how predictable the plot was in Prometheus and Covenant the path was all but predictable and that made them very interesting to theorize over. But no matter if an alien bursted out of someone's back, throat, traditionally their chest or was surgically extracted. It always felt rather tame and obligatory. Somehow Fede managed to show us in these trailers multiple obligatory alien body horror moments and proves without a shadow of a doubt that as a director you don't have to drastically change a good idea in order to reinvent it.
author: @GTChris
clean_text: the sound effects of the facehugger and chestburster are brutal, love it. i am so happy to see the franchise in the hands of someone who truly gets why alien and aliens are such masterpieces in their own right. you can literally watch aliens first and alien second and it would take away little from the overall experience. to seemingly be able to capture the essence of both movies and still manage to bring your own style into it by for instance leaning into the body horror. then even go big on the practical and not get caught into doing it all with cgi. fede is already making history within the franchise with what we have seen so far, that is impressive. i thought i would never see the day that i would be counting the days to go see an alien movie once again. i thought that ship had sailed and the abstract vision ridley scott gave us deserves praise too. despite how predictable the plot was in prometheus and covenant the path was all but predictable and that made them very interesting to theorize over. but no matter if an alien bursted out of someone is back, throat, traditionally their chest or was surgically extracted. it always felt rather tame and obligatory. somehow fede managed to show us in these trailers multiple obligatory alien body horror moments and proves without a shadow of a doubt that as a director you do not have to drastically change a good idea in order to reinvent it.

Nicholas Hoult : "Another movie where I have to fight against Dracula. Wait ? He's not played by Nicolas Cage and his name is Count Orlock ? What ?"
Willem Dafoe : "Yeah because the original movie was an adaptation from Bram Stoker's original book made without his authorisation so they made some changes..."
Nicholas : "Hold up. You seems to really know your subject..."
Willem Dafoe : "Yeah, I'm the guy who play this version of Dracula in the movie Shadow of the vampire."
Nicholas : "Oh so you were Count Orlock ?"
Willem Dafoe : "No no no I played the guy who played him in the original movie. His name was Max Schreck and some people thought he was a true vampire !"
Christopher Walken : "I played Max Schreck too."
Willem Dafoe : "Oh really ?"
Christopher : "And I fought Batman and Catwoman."

text: This was my late grandfathers favourite movie series of all time. He had dementia and he could watch any of the 3 over and over again without getting tired of them, which was very rare even though his short term memory was non existent. We were both looking forward to this movie, so it was disappointing to say the least when they delayed the movie for so long, considering it had finished filming in 2021. He won‚Äôt ever be able to watch this movie unfortunately, as he passed away in May last year. And now you have released the trailer on his birthday, of all days.. which brings a smile to my face. text:
I remember my parents buying me the VHS box sets for the original Bonds when I was younger and obsessing over them. Every time a new Bond came out, my dad and I would get tickets and go to the theatre together, it's still something we look forward to. When Craig was announced as the new Bond, I remember so many critics hating the idea almost writing the series off. 15 years later, the decision to cast Daniel Craig as Bond, in my opinion, holds up as the best direction the series has ever taken. The original Bonds were mostly quirky, fun and a young boys fantasy but Daniel Craig's Bond has emotion, he has grit, he's human. The fun gadgets and espionage that helped me fall in love with the series are still there but in a more reasonable dosage and Craig, as this more grounded Bond, continually keeps me engaged.

Thank you Mr. Craig for not only taking care of this series but moving it to the next level, setting a high standard for the franchise's future. I cannot wait for No Time To Die!

Mathematically speaking it‚Äôs usually one on one off with the bond series. The first in the series starts off with a bang (casino royale) then the next one ends with a whimper (quantum of solace). 

Skyfall was great, Spectre not so much. 
So here‚Äôs hoping NTTD will be a hit. 
Judging by the trailer I‚Äôm confident it will be a fitting conclusion to the Craig-era of bond films. The late Sir Roger Moore holds the distinction of starring in the most bond films but Craig has played the role for the last 15 years. It‚Äôs been 15 years since casino royale. 
Can y‚Äôall believe it? How mad is that. 

Craig is certainly my favourite bond. Let‚Äôs hope this film gives him the send off he deserves.

text:
I am from India, and my aunts tell me this story from the mid 80's when one of my Uncles, brought over a VHS tape, without a cover. He was trying to learn English by watching Hollywood Films. One afternoon he came back with a VHS tape without any cover and title 'College Girls'. He called my two aunts (19 and 22 at that time) and proudly proclaimed, "Sisters, I have this movie that is about college girls, just like you.". The whole family gathered to watch it. The tape was played and promptly destroyed within 10 minutes of its viewing. 

I dont know why this trailer reminded me of that story.

text:
Loving the Pavlovian bell throughout the trailer.

>The discovery of classical conditioning was accidental. While researching the digestion of dogs, Pavlov observed that the dogs' physical responses to food gradually changed. Initially, the dogs only salivated when the food was directly presented. However, he later noticed that the dogs began to salivate slightly before the food arrived in response to sounds consistently associated with feeding, such as the sound of the food cart. To test his theory, Pavlov conducted an experiment where he rang a bell shortly before presenting food to the dogs. Initially, the dogs did not salivate in response to the bell. However, as they learned to associate the sound of the bell with the arrival of food, they began to salivate at the sound alone.
